[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] Distributed TSDB and Query Engine, Prometheus Sidecar, Metrics Aggregator, and more such as Graphite storage and query engine.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] You can find recordings of past meetups here: https://vimeo.com/user/120001164/folder/2290331.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] The simplest and quickest way to try M3 is to use Docker, read the M3 quickstart section for other options.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] This example uses jq to format the output of API calls.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] The below is a simplified version of the M3 quickstart guide, and we suggest you read that for more details.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] M3 welcomes pull requests, read contributing guide to help you get setup for building and contributing to M3.
[src:m3db/blob-readme-md] This project is released under the Apache License, Version 2.0.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] A **distributed database** is a database in which data is stored across different physical locations.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] It may be stored in multiple computers located in the same physical location (e.g. a data centre); or maybe dispersed over a network of interconnected computers.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Unlike parallel systems, in which the processors are tightly coupled and constitute a single database system, a distributed database system consists of loosely coupled sites that share no physical components.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] System administrators can distribute collections of data (e.g. in a database) across multiple physical locations.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] A distributed database can reside on organised network servers or decentralised independent computers on the Internet, on corporate intranets or extranets, or on other organisation networks.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Because distributed databases store data across multiple computers, distributed databases may improve performance at end-user worksites by allowing transactions to be processed on many machines, instead of being limited to one.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Two processes ensure that the distributed databases remain up-to-date and current: replication and duplication.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Duplication, on the other hand, has less complexity.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] It identifies one database as a master and then duplicates that database.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] The duplication process is normally done at a set time after hours.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] This is to ensure that each distributed location has the same data.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] In the duplication process, users may change only the master database.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] This ensures that local data will not be overwritten.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Both replication and duplication can keep the data current in all distributive locations.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Besides distributed database replication and fragmentation, there are many other distributed database design technologies.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] For example, local autonomy, synchronous, and asynchronous distributed database technologies.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] The implementation of these technologies can and do depend on the needs of the business and the sensitivity/confidentiality of the data stored in the database and the price the business is willing to spend on ensuring data security, consistency and integrity.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] In the shared-memory and shared-disk architectures, the data is not partitioned, but it has to be in a shared-nothing architecture.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Shared-disk architecture is more common for cloud databases than for on-premise.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] Historically, shared-nothing was the first architecture to be implemented on the cloud, before the advent of shared cloud storage made shared-disk possible.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] In practice, different layers of the database can have different architectures.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] It is now common to have a compute layer with a shared nothing architecture, and a storage layer with a shared disk architecture.
[src:m3db/distributed-database] This is for instance the case of Snowflake and AWS Aurora.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **metric space** is a set together with a notion of distance between its points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The distance is measured by a function called a **metric** or **distance function**.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces are a general setting for studying many of the concepts of mathematical analysis and geometry.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The most familiar example of a metric space is 3-dimensional Euclidean space with its usual notion of distance.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Other well-known examples are a sphere equipped with the angular distance and the hyperbolic plane.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric may correspond to a metaphorical, rather than physical, notion of distance.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of 100-character Unicode strings can be equipped with the Hamming distance, which measures the number of characters that need to be changed to get from one string to another.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces appear in many different branches of mathematics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, Riemannian manifolds, normed vector spaces, and graphs may be viewed as metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In abstract algebra, the field of *p*-adic numbers is the completion of the field of rational numbers with respect to a certain metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces are also studied in their own right in **metric geometry** and **analysis on metric spaces**.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Many notions of analysis, including balls, completeness, as well as uniform, Lipschitz, and Hölder continuity can be defined for metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Other notions, such as continuity, compactness, and open and closed sets can be defined for metric spaces, but also in the even more general setting of topological spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] To see the utility of different notions of distance, consider the surface of the Earth as a set of points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] We can measure the distance between two such points by the length of the shortest path along the surface, "as the crow flies"; this is particularly useful for shipping and aviation.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] We can also measure the straight-line distance between two points through the Earth's interior; this notion is, for example, natural in seismology, since it roughly corresponds to the length of time it takes for seismic waves to travel between those two points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The notion of distance encoded by the metric space axioms has relatively few requirements.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This generality gives metric spaces a lot of flexibility.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] At the same time, the notion is strong enough to encode many intuitive facts about what distance means.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This means that general results about metric spaces can be applied in many different contexts.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Like many fundamental mathematical concepts, the metric on a metric space can be interpreted in many different ways.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The triangle inequality holds: $d(x,z)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,z)$ This is a natural property of both physical and metaphorical notions of distance: you can arrive at z from x by taking a detour through y, but this will not make your journey any shorter than the direct path.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] It is traditional to write M as an abbreviation for (*M*, *d*) when it is understood what d is.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The real numbers with the distance function $d(x,y)=|y-x|$ given by the absolute difference form a metric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Many properties of metric spaces and functions between them are generalizations of concepts in real analysis and coincide with those concepts when applied to the real line.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ can be equipped with many different metrics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The *taxicab* or *Manhattan* distance is defined by $d_{1}((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=|x_{2}-x_{1}|+|y_{2}-y_{1}|$ and can be thought of as the distance you need to travel along horizontal and vertical lines to get from one point to the other, as illustrated at the top of the article.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The *maximum*, $L^{\infty }$ , or *Chebyshev distance* is defined by $d_{\infty }((x_{1},y_{1}),(x_{2},y_{2}))=\max\{|x_{2}-x_{1}|,|y_{2}-y_{1}|\}.$ This distance does not have an easy explanation in terms of paths in the plane, but it still satisfies the metric space axioms.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] It can be thought of similarly to the number of moves a king would have to make on a chess board to travel from one point to another on the given space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In fact, these three distances, while they have distinct properties, are similar in some ways.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Informally, points that are close in one are close in the others, too.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This observation can be quantified with the formula $d_{\infty }(p,q)\leq d_{2}(p,q)\leq d_{1}(p,q)\leq 2d_{\infty }(p,q),$ which holds for every pair of points $p,q\in \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Moreover, there exists a continuous family of distances $d_{\alpha }$ for $\alpha \in (1,\infty )$ that interpolates between these three distances.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A radically different distance can be defined by setting $d(p,q)={\begin{cases}0,&{\text{if }}p=q,\\1,&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ In this *discrete metric*, all distinct points are 1 unit apart: none of them are close to each other, and none of them are very far away from each other either.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Intuitively, the discrete metric no longer remembers that the set is a plane, but treats it just as an undifferentiated set of points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] All of these metrics can be easily extended to make sense on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ as well as $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Given a metric space (*M*, *d*) and a subset $A\subseteq M$ , we can consider A to be a metric space by measuring distances the same way we would in M.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Two more useful examples are the open interval (0, 1) and the closed interval [0, 1] thought of as subspaces of the real line.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Arthur Cayley, in his article "On Distance", extended metric concepts beyond Euclidean geometry into domains bounded by a conic in a projective space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] His distance was given by logarithm of a cross ratio.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Any projectivity leaving the conic stable also leaves the cross ratio constant, so isometries are implicit.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This method provides models for elliptic geometry and hyperbolic geometry, and Felix Klein, in several publications, established the field of non-euclidean geometry through the use of the Cayley-Klein metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The idea of an abstract space with metric properties was addressed in 1906 by René Maurice Fréchet and the term *metric space* was coined by Felix Hausdorff in 1914.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Fréchet's work laid the foundation for understanding convergence, continuity, and other key concepts in non-geometric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This allowed mathematicians to study functions and sequences in a broader and more flexible way.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This was important for the growing field of functional analysis.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Mathematicians like Hausdorff and Stefan Banach further refined and expanded the framework of metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Hausdorff introduced topological spaces as a generalization of metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Banach's work in functional analysis heavily relied on the metric structure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Over time, metric spaces became a central part of modern mathematics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] They have influenced various fields including topology, geometry, and applied mathematics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces continue to play a crucial role in the study of abstract mathematical concepts.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A distance function is enough to define notions of closeness and convergence that were first developed in real analysis.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Properties that depend on the structure of a metric space are referred to as *metric properties*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Every metric space is also a topological space, and some metric properties can also be rephrased without reference to distance in the language of topology; that is, they are really topological properties.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For any point x in a metric space M and any real number *r* > 0, the *open ball* of radius r around x is defined to be the set of points that are strictly less than distance r from x: $B_{r}(x)=\{y\in M:d(x,y)<r\}.$ This is a natural way to define a set of points that are relatively close to x.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Therefore, a set $N\subseteq M$ is a *neighborhood* of x (informally, it contains all points "close enough" to x) if it contains an open ball of radius r around x for some *r* > 0.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] An *open set* is a set which is a neighborhood of all its points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] It follows that the open balls form a base for a topology on M.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, the open sets of M are exactly the unions of open balls.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] As in any topology, closed sets are the complements of open sets.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Sets may be both open and closed as well as neither open nor closed.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This topology does not carry all the information about the metric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the distances *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ defined above all induce the same topology on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , although they behave differently in many respects.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Similarly, $\mathbb {R}$ with the Euclidean metric and its subspace the interval (0, 1) with the induced metric are homeomorphic but have very different metric properties.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Conversely, not every topological space can be given a metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Topological spaces which are compatible with a metric are called *metrizable* and are particularly well-behaved in many ways: in particular, they are paracompact Hausdorff spaces (hence normal) and first-countable.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The Nagata–Smirnov metrization theorem gives a characterization of metrizability in terms of other topological properties, without reference to metrics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In metric spaces, both of these definitions make sense and they are equivalent.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This is a general pattern for topological properties of metric spaces: while they can be defined in a purely topological way, there is often a way that uses the metric which is easier to state or more familiar from real analysis.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Informally, a metric space is *complete* if it has no "missing points": every sequence that looks like it should converge to something actually converges.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] To make this precise: a sequence (*xn*) in a metric space M is a Cauchy sequence if for every ε > 0 there is an integer N such that for all *m*, *n* > *N*, *d*(*xm*, *xn*) < ε.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] By the triangle inequality, any convergent sequence is a Cauchy sequence: if xm and xn are both less than ε away from the limit, then they are less than 2ε away from each other.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] If the converse is true—every Cauchy sequence in M converges—then M is complete.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Euclidean spaces are complete, as is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ with the other metrics described above.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Two examples of spaces which are not complete are (0, 1) and the rationals, each with the metric induced from $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] One can think of (0, 1) as "missing" its endpoints 0 and 1.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The rationals are missing all the irrationals, since any irrational has a sequence of rationals converging to it in $\mathbb {R}$ (for example, its successive decimal approximations).
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] These examples show that completeness is *not* a topological property, since $\mathbb {R}$ is complete but the homeomorphic space (0, 1) is not.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This notion of "missing points" can be made precise.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In fact, every metric space has a unique *completion*, which is a complete space that contains the given space as a dense subset.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, [0, 1] is the completion of (0, 1), and the real numbers are the completion of the rationals.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Since complete spaces are generally easier to work with, completions are important throughout mathematics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, in abstract algebra, the *p*-adic numbers are defined as the completion of the rationals under a different metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Completion is particularly common as a tool in functional analysis.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Often one has a set of nice functions and a way of measuring distances between them.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Taking the completion of this metric space gives a new set of functions which may be less nice, but nevertheless useful because they behave similarly to the original nice functions in important ways.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, weak solutions to differential equations typically live in a completion (a Sobolev space) rather than the original space of nice functions for which the differential equation actually makes sense.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is *bounded* if there is an r such that no pair of points in M is more than distance r apart.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The least such r is called the diameter of M.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The space M is called *precompact* or *totally bounded* if for every *r* > 0 there is a finite cover of M by open balls of radius r.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] To see this, start with a finite cover by r-balls for some arbitrary r.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Since the subset of M consisting of the centers of these balls is finite, it has finite diameter, say D.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] By the triangle inequality, the diameter of the whole space is at most *D* + 2*r*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The converse does not hold: an example of a metric space that is bounded but not totally bounded is $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (or any other infinite set) with the discrete metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Compactness is a topological property which generalizes the properties of a closed and bounded subset of Euclidean space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is compact if every sequence has a convergent subsequence.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space M is compact if it is complete and totally bounded.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] One example of a compact space is the closed interval [0, 1].
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Compactness is important for similar reasons to completeness: it makes it easy to find limits.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Another important tool is Lebesgue's number lemma, which shows that for any open cover of a compact space, every point is relatively deep inside one of the sets of the cover.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Unlike in the case of topological spaces or algebraic structures such as groups or rings, there is no single "right" type of structure-preserving function between metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Instead, one works with different types of functions depending on one's goals.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The words "function" and "map" are used interchangeably.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] It follows from the metric space axioms that a distance-preserving function is injective.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A bijective distance-preserving function is called an *isometry*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] If there is an isometry between the spaces *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *isometric*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric spaces that are isometric are essentially identical.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other end of the spectrum, one can forget entirely about the metric structure and study continuous maps, which only preserve topological structure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] There are several equivalent definitions of continuity for metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A *homeomorphism* is a continuous bijection whose inverse is also continuous; if there is a homeomorphism between *M*1 and *M*2, they are said to be *homeomorphic*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Homeomorphic spaces are the same from the point of view of topology, but may have very different metric properties.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R}$ is unbounded and complete, while (0, 1) is bounded but not complete.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The only difference between this definition and the ε–δ definition of continuity is the order of quantifiers: the choice of δ must depend only on ε and not on the point x.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] However, this subtle change makes a big difference.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, uniformly continuous maps take Cauchy sequences in *M*1 to Cauchy sequences in *M*2.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, uniform continuity preserves some metric properties which are not purely topological.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the Heine–Cantor theorem states that if *M*1 is compact, then every continuous map is uniformly continuous.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In other words, uniform continuity cannot distinguish any non-topological features of compact metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A Lipschitz map is one that stretches distances by at most a bounded factor.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, a curve in a metric space is rectifiable (has finite length) if and only if it has a Lipschitz reparametrization.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A 1-Lipschitz map is sometimes called a *nonexpanding* or *metric map*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Metric maps are commonly taken to be the morphisms of the category of metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A K-Lipschitz map for *K* < 1 is called a *contraction*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that if M is a complete metric space, then every contraction $f:M\to M$ admits a unique fixed point.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A quasi-isometry is a map that preserves the "large-scale structure" of a metric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Quasi-isometries need not be continuous.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ and its subspace $\mathbb {Z} ^{2}$ are quasi-isometric, even though one is connected and the other is discrete.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The equivalence relation of quasi-isometry is important in geometric group theory: the Švarc–Milnor lemma states that all spaces on which a group acts geometrically are quasi-isometric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A normed vector space is a vector space equipped with a *norm*, which is a function that measures the length of vectors.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The norm of a vector v is typically denoted by $\lVert v\rVert$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Any normed vector space can be equipped with a metric in which the distance between two vectors x and y is given by $d(x,y):=\lVert x-y\rVert .$ The metric d is said to be *induced* by the norm $\lVert {\cdot }\rVert$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] then ${\displaystyle \lVert x\rVert$ is a norm induced by the metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A similar relationship holds between seminorms and pseudometrics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Among examples of metrics induced by a norm are the metrics *d*1, *d*2, and *d*∞ on $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , which are induced by the Manhattan norm, the Euclidean norm, and the maximum norm, respectively.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] More generally, the Kuratowski embedding allows one to see any metric space as a subspace of a normed vector space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Infinite-dimensional normed vector spaces, particularly spaces of functions, are studied in functional analysis.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Completeness is particularly important in this context: a complete normed vector space is known as a Banach space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] An unusual property of normed vector spaces is that linear transformations between them are continuous if and only if they are Lipschitz.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Such transformations are known as bounded operators.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A curve in a metric space (*M*, *d*) is a continuous function ${\displaystyle \gamma$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The length of γ is measured by $L(\gamma )=\sup _{0=x_{0}<x_{1}<\cdots <x_{n}=T}\left\{\sum _{k=1}^{n}d(\gamma (x_{k-1}),\gamma (x_{k}))\right\}.$ In general, this supremum may be infinite; a curve of finite length is called *rectifiable*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Suppose that the length of the curve γ is equal to the distance between its endpoints—that is, it is the shortest possible path between its endpoints.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] After reparametrization by arc length, γ becomes a *geodesic*: a curve which is a distance-preserving function.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A geodesic is a shortest possible path between any two of its points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A *geodesic metric space* is a metric space which admits a geodesic between any two of its points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{2})$ , geodesics are unique, but in $(\mathbb {R} ^{2},d_{1})$ , there are often infinitely many geodesics between two points, as shown in the figure at the top of the article.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The space M is a *length space* (or the metric d is *intrinsic*) if the distance between any two points x and y is the infimum of lengths of paths between them.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Unlike in a geodesic metric space, the infimum does not have to be attained.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] An example of a length space which is not geodesic is the Euclidean plane minus the origin: the points (1, 0) and (-1, 0) can be joined by paths of length arbitrarily close to 2, but not by a path of length 2.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] An example of a metric space which is not a length space is given by the straight-line metric on the sphere: the straight line between two points through the center of the Earth is shorter than any path along the surface.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Given any metric space (*M*, *d*), one can define a new, intrinsic distance function *d*intrinsic on M by setting the distance between points x and y to be the infimum of the d-lengths of paths between them.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For instance, if d is the straight-line distance on the sphere, then *d*intrinsic is the great-circle distance.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] However, in some cases *d*intrinsic may have infinite values.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, if M is the Koch snowflake with the subspace metric d induced from $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , then the resulting intrinsic distance is infinite for any pair of distinct points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A Riemannian manifold is a space equipped with a Riemannian metric tensor, which determines lengths of tangent vectors at every point.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This can be thought of defining a notion of distance infinitesimally.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This construction generalizes to other kinds of infinitesimal metrics on manifolds, such as sub-Riemannian and Finsler metrics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The Riemannian metric is uniquely determined by the distance function; this means that in principle, all information about a Riemannian manifold can be recovered from its distance function.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] One direction in metric geometry is finding purely metric ("synthetic") formulations of properties of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, a Riemannian manifold is a CAT(*k*) space (a synthetic condition which depends purely on the metric) if and only if its sectional curvature is bounded above by k.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Thus CAT(*k*) spaces generalize upper curvature bounds to general metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Real analysis makes use of both the metric on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and the Lebesgue measure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Therefore, generalizations of many ideas from analysis naturally reside in metric measure spaces: spaces that have both a measure and a metric which are compatible with each other.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Formally, a *metric measure space* is a metric space equipped with a Borel regular measure such that every ball has positive measure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example Euclidean spaces of dimension n, and more generally n-dimensional Riemannian manifolds, naturally have the structure of a metric measure space, equipped with the Lebesgue measure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Certain fractal metric spaces such as the Sierpiński gasket can be equipped with the α-dimensional Hausdorff measure where α is the Hausdorff dimension.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In general, however, a metric space may not have an "obvious" choice of measure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] One application of metric measure spaces is generalizing the notion of Ricci curvature beyond Riemannian manifolds.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Just as CAT(*k*) and Alexandrov spaces generalize sectional curvature bounds, RCD spaces are a class of metric measure spaces which generalize lower bounds on Ricci curvature.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A metric space is *discrete* if its induced topology is the discrete topology.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Although many concepts, such as completeness and compactness, are not interesting for such spaces, they are nevertheless an object of study in several branches of mathematics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In particular, finite metric spaces (those having a finite number of points) are studied in combinatorics and theoretical computer science.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Embeddings in other metric spaces are particularly well-studied.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, not every finite metric space can be isometrically embedded in a Euclidean space or in Hilbert space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, in the worst case the required distortion (bilipschitz constant) is only logarithmic in the number of points.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For any undirected connected graph G, the set V of vertices of G can be turned into a metric space by defining the distance between vertices x and y to be the length of the shortest edge path connecting them.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In graph theory, this is also called the shortest-path distance or geodesic distance.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In geometric group theory this construction is applied to the Cayley graph of a (typically infinite) finitely-generated group, yielding the word metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Up to quasi-isometry, the word metric depends only on the group and not on the chosen finite generating set.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] An important area of study in finite metric spaces is the embedding of complex metric spaces into simpler ones while controlling the distortion of distances.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This is particularly useful in computer science and discrete mathematics, where algorithms often perform more efficiently on simpler structures like tree metrics.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A significant result in this area is that any finite metric space can be probabilistically embedded into a *tree metric* with an expected distortion of $O(\log n)$ , where n is the number of points in the metric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This embedding is notable because it achieves the best possible asymptotic bound on distortion, matching the lower bound of $\Omega (\log n)$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The tree metrics produced in this embedding *dominate* the original metrics, meaning that distances in the tree are greater than or equal to those in the original space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] This property is particularly useful for designing approximation algorithms, as it allows for the preservation of distance-related properties while simplifying the underlying structure.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The technique involves constructing a hierarchical decomposition of the original metric space and converting it into a tree metric via a randomized algorithm.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The $O(\log n)$ distortion bound has led to improved approximation ratios in several algorithmic problems, demonstrating the practical significance of this theoretical result.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In modern mathematics, one often studies spaces whose points are themselves mathematical objects.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A distance function on such a space generally aims to measure the dissimilarity between two objects.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The idea of spaces of mathematical objects can also be applied to subsets of a metric space, as well as metric spaces themselves.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Hausdorff and Gromov–Hausdorff distance define metrics on the set of compact subsets of a metric space and the set of compact metric spaces, respectively.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Suppose (*M*, *d*) is a metric space, and let S be a subset of M.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The *distance from S to a point x of M* is, informally, the distance from x to the closest point of S.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] However, since there may not be a single closest point, it is defined via an infimum: $d(x,S)=\inf\{d(x,s):s\in S\}.$ In particular, $d(x,S)=0$ if and only if x belongs to the closure of S.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Furthermore, distances between points and sets satisfy a version of the triangle inequality: $d(x,S)\leq d(x,y)+d(y,S),$ and therefore the map $d_{S}:M\to \mathbb {R}$ defined by $d_{S}(x)=d(x,S)$ is continuous.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Incidentally, this shows that metric spaces are completely regular.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Given two subsets S and T of M, their *Hausdorff distance* is $d_{H}(S,T)=\max\{\sup\{d(s,T):s\in S\},\sup\{d(t,S):t\in T\}\}.$ Informally, two sets S and T are close to each other in the Hausdorff distance if no element of S is too far from T and vice versa.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, if S is an open set in Euclidean space T is an ε-net inside S, then $d_{H}(S,T)<\varepsilon$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In general, the Hausdorff distance $d_{H}(S,T)$ can be infinite or zero.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] However, the Hausdorff distance between two distinct compact sets is always positive and finite.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Thus the Hausdorff distance defines a metric on the set of compact subsets of M.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The Gromov–Hausdorff metric defines a distance between (isometry classes of) compact metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The *Gromov–Hausdorff distance* between compact spaces X and Y is the infimum of the Hausdorff distance over all metric spaces Z that contain X and Y as subspaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] While the exact value of the Gromov–Hausdorff distance is rarely useful to know, the resulting topology has found many applications.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] By the equivalence of norms in finite dimensions, a topologically equivalent metric is obtained if N is the taxicab norm, a p-norm, the maximum norm, or any other norm which is non-decreasing as the coordinates of a positive n-tuple increase (yielding the triangle inequality).
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The topological product of uncountably many metric spaces need not be metrizable.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, an uncountable product of copies of $\mathbb {R}$ is not first-countable and thus is not metrizable.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] If M is a metric space with metric d, and $\sim$ is an equivalence relation on M, then we can endow the quotient set $M/\!\sim$ with a pseudometric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] In general this will only define a pseudometric, i.e. $d'([x],[y])=0$ does not necessarily imply that $[x]=[y]$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] However, for some equivalence relations (e.g., those given by gluing together polyhedra along faces), $d'$ is a metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The quotient metric $d'$ is characterized by the following universal property.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] The quotient metric does not always induce the quotient topology.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] For example, the topological quotient of the metric space $\mathbb {N} \times [0,1]$ identifying all points of the form $(n,0)$ is not metrizable since it is not first-countable, but the quotient metric is a well-defined metric on the same set which induces a coarser topology.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] Moreover, different metrics on the original topological space (a disjoint union of countably many intervals) lead to different topologies on the quotient.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p01] A topological space is sequential if and only if it is a (topological) quotient of a metric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] There are several notions of spaces which have less structure than a metric space, but more than a topological space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] There are also numerous ways of relaxing the axioms for a metric, giving rise to various notions of generalized metric spaces.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] These generalizations can also be combined.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The terminology used to describe them is not completely standardized.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Most notably, in functional analysis pseudometrics often come from seminorms on vector spaces, and so it is natural to call them "semimetrics".
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] This conflicts with the use of the term in topology.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Some authors define metrics so as to allow the distance function d to attain the value ∞, i.e. distances are non-negative numbers on the extended real number line.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Such a function is also called an *extended metric* or "∞-metric".
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Every extended metric can be replaced by a real-valued metric that is topologically equivalent.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] This can be done using a subadditive monotonically increasing bounded function which is zero at zero, e.g. $d'(x,y)=d(x,y)/(1+d(x,y))$ or $d''(x,y)=\min(1,d(x,y))$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] These generalizations still induce a uniform structure on the space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A *pseudometric* on X is a function $d:X\times X\to \mathbb {R}$ which satisfies the axioms for a metric, except that instead of the second (identity of indiscernibles) only $d(x,x)=0$ for all *x* is required.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] In some contexts, pseudometrics are referred to as *semimetrics* because of their relation to seminorms.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Occasionally, a **quasimetric** is defined as a function that satisfies all axioms for a metric with the possible exception of symmetry.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The name of this generalisation is not entirely standardized.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] For example, given a set X of mountain villages, the typical walking times between elements of X form a quasimetric because travel uphill takes longer than travel downhill.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Another example is the length of car rides in a city with one-way streets: here, a shortest path from point A to point B goes along a different set of streets than a shortest path from B to A and may have a different length.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A quasimetric on the reals can be defined by setting $d(x,y)={\begin{cases}x-y&{\text{if }}x\geq y,\\1&{\text{otherwise.}}\end{cases}}$ The 1 may be replaced, for example, by infinity or by $1+{\sqrt {y-x}}$ or any other subadditive function of *y*-*x*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] This quasimetric describes the cost of modifying a metal stick: it is easy to reduce its size by filing it down, but it is difficult or impossible to grow it.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Given a quasimetric on X, one can define an R-ball around x to be the set $\{y\in X|d(x,y)\leq R\}$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] As in the case of a metric, such balls form a basis for a topology on X, but this topology need not be metrizable.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] For example, the topology induced by the quasimetric on the reals described above is the (reversed) Sorgenfrey line.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] In a *metametric*, all the axioms of a metric are satisfied except that the distance between identical points is not necessarily zero.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Metametrics appear in the study of Gromov hyperbolic metric spaces and their boundaries.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The *visual metametric* on such a space satisfies $d(x,x)=0$ for points x on the boundary, but otherwise $d(x,x)$ is approximately the distance from *x* to the boundary.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Metametrics were first defined by Jussi Väisälä.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] In other work, a function satisfying these axioms is called a *partial metric* or a *dislocated metric*.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequality implies the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality (assuming the first axiom), and the ρ-relaxed triangle inequality implies the 2ρ-inframetric inequality.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Semimetrics satisfying these equivalent conditions have sometimes been referred to as *quasimetrics*, *nearmetrics* or **inframetrics**.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The ρ-inframetric inequalities were introduced to model round-trip delay times in the internet.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The triangle inequality implies the 2-inframetric inequality, and the ultrametric inequality is exactly the 1-inframetric inequality.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Sometimes it is used to refer to other generalizations of metrics such as pseudosemimetrics or pseudometrics; in translations of Russian books it sometimes appears as "prametric".
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A premetric that satisfies symmetry, i.e. a pseudosemimetric, is also called a distance.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Any premetric gives rise to a topology as follows.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A set is called *open* if for any point *p* in the set there is an r -ball centered at *p* which is contained in the set.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Every premetric space is a topological space, and in fact a sequential space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] In general, the r -balls themselves need not be open sets with respect to this topology.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] This defines a premetric on the power set of a premetric space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] If we start with a (pseudosemi-)metric space, we get a pseudosemimetric, i.e. a symmetric premetric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The prefixes *pseudo-*, *quasi-* and *semi-* can also be combined, e.g., a **pseudoquasimetric** (sometimes called **hemimetric**) relaxes both the indiscernibility axiom and the symmetry axiom and is simply a premetric satisfying the triangle inequality.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] For pseudoquasimetric spaces the open r -balls form a basis of open sets.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A very basic example of a pseudoquasimetric space is the set $\{0,1\}$ with the premetric given by $d(0,1)=1$ and $d(1,0)=0.$ The associated topological space is the Sierpiński space.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Sets equipped with an extended pseudoquasimetric were studied by William Lawvere as "generalized metric spaces".
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] From a categorical point of view, the extended pseudometric spaces and the extended pseudoquasimetric spaces, along with their corresponding nonexpansive maps, are the best behaved of the metric space categories.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] One can take arbitrary products and coproducts and form quotient objects within the given category.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] If one drops "extended", one can only take finite products and coproducts.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] If one drops "pseudo", one cannot take quotients.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Lawvere also gave an alternate definition of such spaces as enriched categories.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The ordered set $(\mathbb {R} ,\geq )$ can be seen as a category with one morphism $a\to b$ if $a\geq b$ and none otherwise.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Using + as the tensor product and 0 as the identity makes this category into a monoidal category $R^{*}$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] The notion of a metric can be generalized from a distance between two elements to a number assigned to a multiset of elements.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A multiset is a generalization of the notion of a set in which an element can occur more than once.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] Define the multiset union $U=XY$ as follows: if an element x occurs m times in X and n times in Y then it occurs *m* + *n* times in U.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] By considering the cases of axioms 1 and 2 in which the multiset X has two elements and the case of axiom 3 in which the multisets X, Y, and Z have one element each, one recovers the usual axioms for a metric.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] That is, every multiset metric yields an ordinary metric when restricted to sets of two elements.
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] A simple example is the set of all nonempty finite multisets X of integers with $d(X)=\max(X)-\min(X)$ .
[src:m3db/metric-mathematics-p02] More complex examples are information distance in multisets; and normalized compression distance (NCD) in multisets.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3 Coordinator is a service that coordinates reads and writes between upstream systems, such as Prometheus, and M3DB.
[src:m3db/overview-components] It is a bridge that users can deploy to access the benefits of M3DB such as long term storage and multi-DC setup with other monitoring systems, such as Prometheus.
[src:m3db/overview-components] See this presentation for more on long term storage in Prometheus.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3DB is a distributed time series database that provides scalable storage and a reverse index of time series.
[src:m3db/overview-components] It is optimized as a cost effective and reliable realtime and long term retention metrics store and index.
[src:m3db/overview-components] For more details, see the M3DB documentation.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3 Query is a distributed query engine for querying realtime and historical data stored in M3DB nodes, supporting several query languages.
[src:m3db/overview-components] It is designed to support both low latency realtime queries and queries that can take longer to execute, aggregating over larger datasets for analytical use cases.
[src:m3db/overview-components] For example, if you are using the Prometheus remote write endpoint with M3 Coordinator, you can use M3 Query instead of the Prometheus remote read endpoint.
[src:m3db/overview-components] By doing so, you get all the benefits of M3 Query’s engine such as block processing.
[src:m3db/overview-components] As M3 Query provides a Prometheus compatible API, you can use 3rd party graphing and alerting solutions like Grafana.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3 Aggregator is a dedicated metrics aggregator that provides stateful stream-based downsampling before storing metrics in M3DB nodes.
[src:m3db/overview-components] It uses leader election and aggregation window tracking, leveraging etcd to manage this state, to reliably emit at-least-once aggregations for downsampled metrics to long term storage.
[src:m3db/overview-components] This provides cost effective and reliable downsampling & roll up of metrics.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3 Coordinator can also perform this role, but M3 Aggregator shards and replicates metrics, whereas M3 Coordinator is not and requires care to deploy and run in a highly available way.
[src:m3db/overview-components] Similar to M3DB, M3 Aggregator supports clustering and replication by default.
[src:m3db/overview-components] This means that metrics are correctly routed to the instance(s) responsible for aggregating each metric and you can configure multiple M3 Aggregator replicas so that there are no single points of failure for aggregation.
[src:m3db/overview-components] M3 Aggregator is in heavy development to make it more usable without requiring you to write your own compatible producer and consumer.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus originated at SoundCloud in 2012 and was accepted by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) in 2016, graduating from incubation in 2018.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] It is commonly paired with Grafana for dashboard visualization and supports a wide range of exporters and integrations.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus was developed at SoundCloud starting in 2012, after the company found that its existing metrics tools, based on StatsD and Graphite, could not meet the demands of its containerized infrastructure.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The design goals included a multi-dimensional data model, operational simplicity, scalable data collection, and a powerful query language in a single tool.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The project was open source from the start and was adopted by Boxever and Docker users before any official announcement.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The design was influenced by Borgmon, Google's internal time-series monitoring system, which treated time-series data as a source for alert generation.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] By 2013, Prometheus was in production use at SoundCloud.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The project was publicly announced in January 2015.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] In May 2016, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation accepted Prometheus as its second incubated project, after Kubernetes.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] In August 2018, the CNCF announced that Prometheus had graduated from incubation.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus 1.0 was released in July 2016.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Subsequent releases through 2016 and 2017 led to Prometheus 2.0 in November 2017, which introduced a new storage engine with significantly improved performance and reduced disk usage.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] A typical Prometheus monitoring deployment consists of several components working together.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Exporters run on monitored hosts to collect and expose local metrics.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The Prometheus server scrapes those exporters at a configured interval, aggregates the data, and stores it locally.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Alertmanager receives alerts from Prometheus and handles routing, grouping, and silencing before forwarding notifications.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Grafana is commonly used to build dashboards from Prometheus data.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Queries against all of these are written in PromQL, Prometheus's native query language.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus data is organized as named metrics, each optionally qualified by an arbitrary number of key-value label pairs.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Labels can identify the data source (server name, datacenter) or carry application-specific context such as HTTP status code, request method, or endpoint.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Querying in real time against any combination of labels is what makes the data model multi-dimensional.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus stores data locally on disk for fast writes and queries.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Metrics can also be forwarded to remote storage backends, including Grafana Mimir and other Prometheus-compatible systems.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus collects data through a pull model: the server periodically queries a configured list of targets (exporters) and aggregates the returned time-series values.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes several service discovery mechanisms to automatically locate targets in dynamic environments.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus provides its own query language, PromQL (Prometheus Query Language), which allows users to select and aggregate time-series data.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The language includes time-oriented constructs such as the rate() function, instant vectors, and range vectors that return multiple samples per series over a specified time window.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Alert rules in Prometheus specify a condition and a duration; if the condition holds for that duration, Prometheus fires an alert to Alertmanager.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Alertmanager handles silencing, inhibition, and routing to notification destinations including email, Slack, and PagerDuty.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Additional targets such as Microsoft Teams can be reached through the Alertmanager webhook receiver interface.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes its own time series database.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Recent data (by default, one to three hours) is held in a combination of memory and mmap-backed files.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Older data is written to persistent blocks indexed with an inverted index, which suits Prometheus's label-based query patterns.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] A background compaction process merges smaller blocks into larger ones to reduce read overhead.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Durability against crashes is provided by a write-ahead log (WAL).
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus includes a basic expression browser but is not a full dashboard system.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Grafana is the standard pairing, querying Prometheus via PromQL to produce dashboards; the need to deploy and maintain Grafana separately is sometimes cited as an operational drawback.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus favors white-box monitoring, where applications publish internal metrics for collection.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Exporters and agents are available for many applications and systems.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] For transition from existing monitoring stacks, Prometheus supports several protocols: Graphite, StatsD, SNMP, JMX, and CollectD.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Metrics are typically retained for a few weeks.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] For longer retention, Prometheus can stream data to remote storage backends.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] An effort to standardize the Prometheus exposition format as OpenMetrics has gained adoption from several vendors, including InfluxData's TICK suite, InfluxDB, Google Cloud Platform, Datadog, and New Relic.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The OpenMetrics specification is maintained separately from the Prometheus project.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] Prometheus client libraries are available for most major programming languages.
[src:m3db/prometheus-software] The POCO C++ Libraries expose Prometheus metrics through the `Poco::Prometheus` namespace.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] A **time series database** is a software system that is optimized for storing and serving time series through associated pairs of time(s) and value(s).
[src:m3db/time-series-database] In some fields, *time series* may be called profiles, curves, traces or trends.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Several early time series databases are associated with industrial applications which could efficiently store measured values from sensory equipment (also referred to as data historians), but now are used in support of a much wider range of applications.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] In many cases, the repositories of time-series data will utilize compression algorithms to manage the data efficiently.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Although it is possible to store time-series data in many different database types, the design of these systems with time as a key index is distinctly different from relational databases which reduce discrete relationships through referential models.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series datasets are relatively large and uniform compared to other datasets―usually being composed of a timestamp and associated data.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series datasets can also have fewer relationships between data entries in different tables and don't require indefinite storage of entries.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] The unique properties of time series datasets mean that time series databases can provide significant improvements in storage space and performance over general purpose databases.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] For instance, due to the uniformity of time series data, specialized compression algorithms can provide improvements over regular compression algorithms designed to work on less uniform data.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series databases can also be configured to regularly delete (or downsample) old data, unlike regular databases which are designed to store data indefinitely.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Special database indices can also provide boosts in query performance.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series databases are commonly designed for append-heavy workloads, where large numbers of measurements or events are continuously written together with timestamps.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Specialized time series management systems have been developed for data from monitoring, automation, the Internet of Things, and cyber-physical systems, where data may be produced at high velocity and in large volumes.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Common design goals include high-throughput data ingestion, low-latency queries over time ranges, efficient compression, and support for aggregation or downsampling over time windows.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Many systems also organize data by tags, devices, sensors, or other metadata, so that users can retrieve measurements by both time range and source.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series databases are used in application areas where data is collected continuously over time.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Examples include industrial monitoring, operational historians, infrastructure and application monitoring, Internet of Things sensor data, energy systems, financial market data, and scientific measurements.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] In monitoring applications, time series database systems may need to process large amounts of sensor or metric data in real time, execute continuous queries, and support analytical tasks such as data exploration, anomaly detection, predictive modeling, trend analysis, and missing-value recovery.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Time series databases are often used as storage and query systems for downstream analytical tasks, including forecasting, anomaly detection, imputation, and pattern matching.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Some systems also integrate analytical or machine-learning functions closer to the database layer, allowing users to invoke forecasting or anomaly detection through database query interfaces such as SQL.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] Recent research in time series analysis has also explored large pre-trained models for tasks such as forecasting, imputation, and anomaly detection.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] These models are usually discussed as analytical methods for time series data rather than as defining features of time series databases.
[src:m3db/time-series-database] The following database systems have functionality optimized for handling time series data.
